g.text: 3D Points
As before, a 3D point can be written in
Inhomogeneous coordinates
Homogeneous coordinates
Again, as before, all homogeneous vectors related by
scale belong to the same equivalent class, and we can
convert them from homogeneous to inhomogeneous coordinates
3D Plane
A 3D plane can be represented in
homogeneous coordinates
Then, we can normalize m so that
Normal perpendicular to
the plane d and d is its
distance to the origin
An exception is given by the
plane at infinity m = (0,0,0,1)^T
which passes through all ideal points for which w = 0
3D Lines
The points on a 3D line can be expressed as a
linear combination of two points p and q
This representation uses 6 parameters
for 4 degrees of freedom
3D Quadrics
The 3D analog of a 2D conics is a quadric surface
It is useful in the study of multi-view geometry
